Narcotics cabinets



We supply narcotics cabinets tested and certified in accordance with standard EN 1143-1 for the legally required safekeeping of narcotics; we have a wide range of different sized free-standing or fitted cabinets with a choice of featured equipment.



It makes sense to buy a safe, but when you start to think seriously about it and look at what the market has to offer, you very quickly realise that you are faced with a huge choice. Different models are suitable for different purposes, and you need to think about the security level, resistance grade and physical size of your safe. When purchasing a safe, you can rely completely on the help and advice of our experts – you will find detailed, all-round information on security levels and types of safe in the section Tips for buying a safe. 
 
Private individuals and business customers 
Some of our customers are private individuals, but many businesses also use and appreciate our products, because numerous branches of industry are subject to special requirements laid down by insurance companies. It can, for example, be mandatory to keep certain valuables or documents in a safe. Banks have always followed this rule, of course, but many other businesses are now also obliged to use a safe, which is also required to meet a certain security level.
There are a number of reasons why private individuals should invest in a safe. Firstly, of course, a safe protects valuables such as jewellery, cash or important documents against theft or other unauthorised access. Secondly, a safe with a fire protection rating also provides protection in other situations. For example, even in the event of a fire, the items in the safe are protected against the effects of heat, flames and extinguishing water, so you will have one thing fewer to worry about. 
 
Size is important
When considering the size of your new safe, please remember to plan for future growth. First determine which items you want to store in the safe now, which will give you the minimum size required.
However, since a safe is a long-term investment, it is vitally important to allow room for expansion. 
 If a business now intends to use a safe for the secure storage of important files, for example, it is possible that other documents will be added as time goes by. The same is true of safes in private homes, whose owners may add more items of jewellery or works of art to their collections.  
In addition, not only the size of the items stored in the safe is an important consideration, but also their value. This is obviously an issue that you should discuss with your insurance company to be sure that your cover is sufficient. However, the safe you choose must also be appropriate to the insurance policy; some companies require the insured items to be kept in a safe with a certain minimum security level. Our experts will be glad to give you the benefit of their wide safe-related experience and advise you about this particular aspect. 














